rt { |item1, item2| item2 \u003C=\u003E item1 }\n  else\n    arr.sort { |item1, item2| item1 \u003C=\u003E item2 }\n  end\nend\n\nbooks = [\"Heart of Darkness\", \"Code Complete\", \"The Lorax\", \"The Prophet\", \"Absalom, Absalom!\", 1]\n\nputs \"A-Z: #{alphabetize(books)}\"\nputs \"Z-A: #{alphabetize(books, true)}\"\n"}],"preview_button":false,"is_current_checkpoint":true},{"_id":"5065d96516aa7a00020ca8ee","index":1,"code_reset":true,"default_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":""}],"entry":"First, we'll need to define our `alphabetize` method.","entry_html":"\u003Cp\u003EFirst, we\u0026#39;ll need to define our \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E method.\u003C/p\u003E\n","external_resources":["https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.7.1/jquery.min.js"],"hint":"Don't forget:\n\n    def method_name(optional parameters)\n      # Do something\n    end","hint_html":"\u003Cp\u003EDon\u0026#39;t forget:\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cpre\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Edef method_name(optional parameters)\n  # Do something\nend\n\u003C/code\u003E\u003C/pre\u003E\n","instruction":"Define `alphabetize` in the editor to the right. It shouldn't take any arguments yet, and there doesn't need to be anything in the body of the method.","instruction_html":"\u003Cp\u003EDefine \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E in the editor to the right. It shouldn\u0026#39;t take any arguments yet, and there doesn\u0026#39;t need to be anything in the body of the method.\u003C/p\u003E\n","name":"Defining Our Method","test_functions":"begin\n  alphabetize\nrescue NameError\n  return \"Did you define a method called alphabetize?\"\nend\n\nif exception.kind_of? SyntaxError\n  return \"It looks like your syntax isn't quite right. Check the first exercise if you need help!\"\nend\n\nreturn true","pro_ad":{"params":{"header":"Not sure where to start?","body":"Let us set you up for success with a personalized learning path.","hint":"Get live, fast support from Codecademy Advisors when you get stuck.","utm_content":"wheretostart","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/codecademy-images/pro/variants-path.svg","utm_campaign":"ad_revamp_apr_2016","utm_source":"codecademy_platform"},"url":"/pro"},"completed":true,"latest_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":"def alphabetize\n\nend"}],"preview_button":false,"is_current_checkpoint":false},{"_id":"5065d96634f50e00020ca924","index":2,"code_reset":false,"default_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":""}],"entry":"Let's start with the new bit of code you saw in exercise 1:\n\n    def alphabetize(arr, rev=false)\n\nThe first part makes sense\u2014we're defining a method, `alphabetize`. We can guess that the first parameter is an `arr`ay, but what's this `rev=false` business?\n\nWhat this does is tell Ruby that `alphabetize` has a second parameter, `rev` (for \"reverse\") that will **default** to `false` if the user doesn't type in two arguments. You might have noticed that our first call to `alphabetize` in exercise 1 was just\n\n    alphabetize(books)\n\nRuby didn't see a `rev`, so it gave it the default value of `false`.","entry_html":"\u003Cp\u003ELet\u0026#39;s start with the new bit of code you saw in exercise 1:\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cpre\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Edef alphabetize(arr, rev=false)\n\u003C/code\u003E\u003C/pre\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EThe first part makes sense\u2014we\u0026#39;re defining a method, \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E. We can guess that the first parameter is an \u003Ccode\u003Earr\u003C/code\u003Eay, but what\u0026#39;s this \u003Ccode\u003Erev=false\u003C/code\u003E business?\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EWhat this does is tell Ruby that \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E has a second parameter, \u003Ccode\u003Erev\u003C/code\u003E (for \u0026quot;reverse\u0026quot;) that will \u003Cstrong\u003Edefault\u003C/strong\u003E to \u003Ccode\u003Efalse\u003C/code\u003E if the user doesn\u0026#39;t type in two arguments. You might have noticed that our first call to \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E in exercise 1 was just\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cpre\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize(books)\n\u003C/code\u003E\u003C/pre\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003ERuby didn\u0026#39;t see a \u003Ccode\u003Erev\u003C/code\u003E, so it gave it the default value of \u003Ccode\u003Efalse\u003C/code\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\n","external_resources":["https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.7.1/jquery.min.js"],"hint":"`arr`, we be pirates.","hint_html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ccode\u003Earr\u003C/code\u003E, we be pirates.\u003C/p\u003E\n","instruction":"Update your `alphabetize` method with two parameters: `arr`, representing the array to be passed in, and `rev`, a boolean that defaults to `false`.","instruction_html":"\u003Cp\u003EUpdate your \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E method with two parameters: \u003Ccode\u003Earr\u003C/code\u003E, representing the array to be passed in, and \u003Ccode\u003Erev\u003C/code\u003E, a boolean that defaults to \u003Ccode\u003Efalse\u003C/code\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\n","name":"Default Parameters","test_functions":"begin\n  alphabetize([1,2,3], true)\nrescue ArgumentError\n  return \"Make sure your method now takes two arguments: an array and a boolean, with the boolean defaulting to false.\"\nend\n\nif method(:alphabetize).parameters[1] == nil || code.scan(\"false\").length == 0\n  return \"Did you make a second argument, rev, that defaults to false?\"\nend\n\nif exception.kind_of? SyntaxError\n  return \"It looks like your syntax isn't quite right. Check the first exercise if you need help!\"\nend\n\nreturn true","pro_ad":{"params":{"header":"Not sure where to start?","body":"Let us set you up for success with a personalized learning path.","hint":"Get live, fast support from Codecademy Advisors when you get stuck.","utm_content":"wheretostart","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/codecademy-images/pro/variants-path.svg","utm_campaign":"ad_revamp_apr_2016","utm_source":"codecademy_platform"},"url":"/pro"},"completed":true,"latest_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":"def alphabetize(arr, rev=false)\n\nend"}],"preview_button":false,"is_current_checkpoint":false},{"_id":"530ea665282ae346360032d3","index":3,"code_reset":false,"default_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":""}],"entry":"Great! Now let's add a little logic to our method.\n\n```ruby\nnumbers = [5, 1, 3, 8]\nnumbers.sort!\nputs numbers\n```\n\n1. In the above example, we create a new array called `numbers`.\n2. Then, we sort the array.\n3. Finally, we print out `1`, `3`, `5`, `8`, the sorted array.\n\nIn Ruby, there are two sorting methods, `.sort` or `sort!`. The first method, `.sort`, simply returns a sorted array while leaving the original array alone. The second method, `.sort!`, modifies the actual array.","entry_html":"\u003Cp\u003EGreat! Now let\u0026#39;s add a little logic to our method.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cpre\u003E\u003Ccode class=\"ruby\"\u003Enumbers = [5, 1, 3, 8]\nnumbers.sort!\nputs numbers\n\u003C/code\u003E\u003C/pre\u003E\n\n\u003Col\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EIn the above example, we create a new array called \u003Ccode\u003Enumbers\u003C/code\u003E.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EThen, we sort the array.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EFinally, we print out \u003Ccode\u003E1\u003C/code\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003E3\u003C/code\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003E5\u003C/code\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003E8\u003C/code\u003E, the sorted array.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003C/ol\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EIn Ruby, there are two sorting methods, \u003Ccode\u003E.sort\u003C/code\u003E or \u003Ccode\u003Esort!\u003C/code\u003E. The first method, \u003Ccode\u003E.sort\u003C/code\u003E, simply returns a sorted array while leaving the original array alone. The second method, \u003Ccode\u003E.sort!\u003C/code\u003E, modifies the actual array.\u003C/p\u003E\n","external_resources":["https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.7.1/jquery.min.js"],"hint":null,"hint_html":null,"instruction":"1. Inside your method, add a line that calls `.sort!` on the `arr` array. Since it is the last line of the method, the sorted array will be returned.\n2. Now test your work! After your method, make a new array called `numbers` that contains a few numbers like the example above.\n3. Call your `alphabetize` method with your `numbers` array as the parameter and `puts` the result to the console.","instruction_html":"\u003Col\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EInside your method, add a line that calls \u003Ccode\u003E.sort!\u003C/code\u003E on the \u003Ccode\u003Earr\u003C/code\u003E array. Since it is the last line of the method, the sorted array will be returned.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003ENow test your work! After your method, make a new array called \u003Ccode\u003Enumbers\u003C/code\u003E that contains a few numbers like the example above.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003ECall your \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E method with your \u003Ccode\u003Enumbers\u003C/code\u003E array as the parameter and \u003Ccode\u003Eputs\u003C/code\u003E the result to the console.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003C/ol\u003E\n","name":"Sorting","test_functions":"if exception.kind_of? SyntaxError\n  return \"It looks like your syntax isn't quite right. Check the first exercise if you need help!\"\nend\n\ntest_array = [\"cockroaches\", \"ants\", \"bees\"]\n\nunless alphabetize(test_array) == [\"ants\", \"bees\", \"cockroaches\"]\n  return \"It looks like your method doesn't default to alphabetizing an array when it doesn't receive a second parameter.\"\nend\n\nif prints.length == 0\n  return \"It looks like you didn't print anything to the console. Does your method use 'puts' to print the sorted array, and did you remember to call your method?\"\nend\n\nreturn true","pro_ad":{"params":{"header":"Not sure where to start?","body":"Let us set you up for success with a personalized learning path.","hint":"Get live, fast support from Codecademy Advisors when you get stuck.","utm_content":"wheretostart","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/codecademy-images/pro/variants-path.svg","utm_campaign":"ad_revamp_apr_2016","utm_source":"codecademy_platform"},"url":"/pro"},"completed":true,"latest_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":"def alphabetize(arr, rev=false)\n   arr.sort!\nend\n\nnumbers = [2,3,4,5,1]\nputs alphabetize(numbers)"}],"preview_button":false,"is_current_checkpoint":false},{"_id":"5065d967f4c9bc00020c9f59","index":4,"code_reset":false,"default_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":""}],"entry":"Great! Now we need to add the right logic to our method.\n\n```ruby\nnumbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\nnumbers.reverse!\nputs numbers\n```\n\n1. In the example above, we create an array called `numbers`.\n2. Then, we reverse the array. Like with `.sort!`, \nthe exclamation mark means we modify the actual array.\n3. Finally, we print out `5`, `4`, `3`, `2`, and `1`.","entry_html":"\u003Cp\u003EGreat! Now we need to add the right logic to our method.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cpre\u003E\u003Ccode class=\"ruby\"\u003Enumbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\nnumbers.reverse!\nputs numbers\n\u003C/code\u003E\u003C/pre\u003E\n\n\u003Col\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EIn the example above, we create an array called \u003Ccode\u003Enumbers\u003C/code\u003E.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EThen, we reverse the array. Like with \u003Ccode\u003E.sort!\u003C/code\u003E, \nthe exclamation mark means we modify the actual array.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EFinally, we print out \u003Ccode\u003E5\u003C/code\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003E4\u003C/code\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003E3\u003C/code\u003E, \u003Ccode\u003E2\u003C/code\u003E, and \u003Ccode\u003E1\u003C/code\u003E.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003C/ol\u003E\n","external_resources":["https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.7.1/jquery.min.js"],"hint":null,"hint_html":null,"instruction":"1. After your `.sort!` call, add an `if` statement. If `rev` is true, call `reverse!` on `arr`.\n\nKeep your `numbers` array and the `puts` statement so that you can see your work in action!","instruction_html":"\u003Col\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EAfter your \u003Ccode\u003E.sort!\u003C/code\u003E call, add an \u003Ccode\u003Eif\u003C/code\u003E statement. If \u003Ccode\u003Erev\u003C/code\u003E is true, call \u003Ccode\u003Ereverse!\u003C/code\u003E on \u003Ccode\u003Earr\u003C/code\u003E.\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003C/ol\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EKeep your \u003Ccode\u003Enumbers\u003C/code\u003E array and the \u003Ccode\u003Eputs\u003C/code\u003E statement so that you can see your work in action!\u003C/p\u003E\n","name":"Sorting With Control Flow","test_functions":"if exception.kind_of? SyntaxError\n  return \"It looks like your syntax isn't quite right. Check the first exercise if you need help!\"\nend\n\nunless code.include? \"reverse\"\n  return \"It looks like you didn't use the `.reverse!` method.\"\nend\n\ntest_array = [\"cockroaches\", \"ants\", \"bees\"]\n\nunless alphabetize(test_array) == [\"ants\", \"bees\", \"cockroaches\"]\n  return \"It looks like your method doesn't default to alphabetizing an array when it doesn't receive a second parameter.\"\nend\n\nunless alphabetize(test_array, false) == [\"ants\", \"bees\", \"cockroaches\"]\n  return \"It looks like your method doesn't alphabetize an array when it receives 'false' as a second parameter.\"\nend\n\nunless alphabetize(test_array, true) == [\"cockroaches\", \"bees\", \"ants\"]\n  return \"It looks like your method doensn't reverse-alphabetize an array when it receives 'true' as a parameter.\"\nend\n\nif prints.length == 0\n  return \"It looks like you didn't print anything to the console. Does your method use 'puts' to print the sorted array, and did you remember to call your method?\"\nend\n\nreturn true","pro_ad":{"params":{"header":"Not sure where to start?","body":"Let us set you up for success with a personalized learning path.","hint":"Get live, fast support from Codecademy Advisors when you get stuck.","utm_content":"wheretostart","image_url":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/codecademy-images/pro/variants-path.svg","utm_campaign":"ad_revamp_apr_2016","utm_source":"codecademy_platform"},"url":"/pro"},"completed":true,"latest_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":"def alphabetize(arr, rev=false)\n   arr.sort!\n    if rev == true\n        arr.reverse!\n    else\n        arr\n    end\nend\n\nnumbers = [2,3,4,5,1]\nputs alphabetize(numbers, false)"}],"preview_button":false,"is_current_checkpoint":false},{"_id":"5065d9697cae5600020cc51f","index":5,"code_reset":false,"default_files":[{"filename":"script.rb","content":""}],"entry":"Well done! You now have your very own method that adds functionality that Ruby didn't have before.\n\nBuilding your own methods is great for using code over and over without having to retype things, but it's also great for **abstracting** or **simplifying** your program. Once you write `alphabetize`, you don't ever have to think about how it works\u2014you just call it whenever you need it.","entry_html":"\u003Cp\u003EWell done! You now have your very own method that adds functionality that Ruby didn\u0026#39;t have before.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EBuilding your own methods is great for using code over and over without having to retype things, but it\u0026#39;s also great for \u003Cstrong\u003Eabstracting\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Esimplifying\u003C/strong\u003E your program. Once you write \u003Ccode\u003Ealphabetize\u003C/code\u003E, you don\u0026#39;t ever have to think about how it works\u2014you just call it whenever you need it.\u003C/p\u003E\n","external_resources":["https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.7.1/jquery.min.js"],"hint":null,"hint_html":null,"instruction":"Click Save \u0026 Submit Code to finish this project and continue your journey toward Ruby Method Mastery.","instruction_html":"\u003Cp\u003EClick Save \u0026amp; Submit Code to finish this project and continue your journey toward Ruby Method Mastery.\u003C/p\u003E\n","name":"You Did It! (For Real This Time)","test_functions":"return true","pro_ad":{"params":{"header":